<section label="sec-sov-method">
	<title> Separation of Variables (SOV) Method </title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			When a differential equation is both <em>first-order</em> and <em>separable</em>, there's a reliable method we can use to find its general solution: the <em>separation of variables</em> method. In essence, this technique works by rewriting the equation so that all the <m>y</m> terms appear on one side and all the <m>x</m> terms on the other. Once this is done, both sides can be integrated, revealing a relationship between <m>y</m> and <m>x</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			The real work is often algebraic—rearranging the equation to achieve this separation. Some equations fall into separable form immediately; others require creative manipulation. But once you're in the right form, the process becomes mechanical: divide, integrate, and (if possible) solve for <m>y</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			This section lays out the general steps of the method and provides several examples to help you master both the process and the algebraic and calculus skills that go with it.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<exercise label="chkpt-sov-method-examples-1">
		<title> When Does SOV Apply? </title>

		<statement>
			<p>
				Which two properties must a differential equation satisfy in order to solve it using the separation of variables method?
			</p>
		</statement>

		<choices>
			<choice>
				<statement>
					<p>
						The equation must be linear and separable.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Incorrect. Separable is required, but the equation does not need to be linear.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice>
				<statement>
					<p>
						The equation must be first-order and linear.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Incorrect. First-order is required, but the equation does not need to be linear for the separation of variables method to be applied.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice>
				<statement>
					<p>
						The equation must be second-order and separable.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Incorrect. Separable is required, but the equation cannot be second-order for the separation of variables method to be applied.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="yes">
				<statement>
					<p>
						The equation must be first-order and separable.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Correct! The separation of variables method applies only to first-order differential equations thatare separable.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</choice>
		</choices>

	</exercise>

	<paragraphs label="sov-method-steps">
		<title> Separation of Variable Method Steps </title>

		<p>
			Once you've confirmed that a differential equation is separable, the process for solving it is remarkably systematic. Here's a step-by-step breakdown of how the separation of variables method works.
		</p>

		<exploration xml:id="sov-method">
			<title>The Separation of Variables Method</title>

			<dl>

				<li xml:id="sov-step-1"><title>Step 1: Verify that the equation is separable</title>
					<p>
						Confirm that the equation is first-order and can be rearranged into the form
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y).
						</me>
						If so, proceed to the next step.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li xml:id="sov-step-2"><title>Step 2: Separate and integrate</title>
					<p>
						Rearrange the equation to isolate all <m>y</m> terms (including <m>dy</m>) on one side and all <m>x</m> terms (including <m>dx</m>) on the other:
					</p>
					<me>
						\int \frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = \int f(x)\ dx.
					</me>
					<p>
						Then integrate both sides.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li xml:id="sov-step-3"><title>Step 3: Solve for <m>y</m></title>
					<p>
						If possible, solve the resulting equation for <m>y</m> explicitly. Otherwise, leave your answer in implicit form. Combine integration constants when appropriate.
					</p>
				</li>

			</dl>
		</exploration>

		<exercise label="chkpt-sov-method-steps-1">
			<title> Place the SOV Tasks in the Correct Order </title>
			
			<statement>
				<p>
					Place the tasks in the order that they should be performed to find the general solution using separation of variables.
				</p>
				<p>
					Drag each task on the left to the correct order on the right.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<feedback>
				<p>
					Review the <xref ref="sov-method" text="custom">SOV Method</xref>.
				</p>
			</feedback>

			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise>
						<p>
							<line><m>\text{Verify the differential}</m></line>
							<line><m>\text{equation is first-order}</m></line>
						</p>
					</premise>
					<response>
						<p>
							<m>\text{Task 1}</m>
						</p>
					</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise>
						<p>
							<line><m>\text{Rewrite the equation as}</m></line>
							<line><m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)g(y)</m></line>
						</p>
					</premise>
					<response>
						<p>
							<m>\text{Task 2}</m>
						</p>
					</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise>
						<p>
							<line><m>\text{Rewrite the equation as}</m></line>
							<line><m>\ds\frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = f(x)\ dx</m></line>
						</p>
					</premise>
					<response>
						<p>
							<m>\text{Task 3}</m>
						</p>
					</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise>
						<p>
							<line><m>\text{Rewrite the equation as}</m></line>
							<line><m>\ds\int \frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = \int f(x)\ dx</m></line>
						</p>
					</premise>
					<response>
						<p>
							<m>\text{Task 4}</m>
						</p>
					</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise>
						<p>
							<line><m>\text{Find the antiderivatives}</m></line>
							<line><m>\text{of }\ds\frac{1}{g(y)} \text{ and } f(x)</m></line>
						</p>
					</premise>
					<response>
						<p>
							<m>\text{Task 5}</m>
						</p>	
					</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise>
						<p>
							<m>\text{If possible, solve for } y</m>
						</p>
					</premise>
					<response>
						<p>
							<m>\text{Task 6}</m>
						</p>
					</response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>

		</exercise>

		<p>
			A common practice in separation of variables is to treat <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> as a fraction and manipulate it like <m>dy = \frac{dy}{dx} dx</m>. While not formally correct, this approach is backed by the chain rule and leads to valid results in this context.
		</p>

		<p>
			Specifically, when we write the separated integrals in <xref ref="sov-step-2" text="custom">step 2</xref> as
		</p>

		<me>
			\int \frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = \int f(x)\ dx,
		</me>

		<p>
			it may look like we are integrating one side with respect to <m>y</m> and the other with respect to <m>x</m>. But what's really happening is that we're integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>, using the differential of <m>y</m>, defined as <m>dy = \frac{dy}{dx} dx</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			To see this more carefully, start with the separable form
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y),
			</me>
			divide both sides by <m>g(y)</m>,
			<me>
				\frac{1}{g(y)} \frac{dy}{dx} = f(x),
			</me>
			and integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives
			<md>
				<mrow> \int \frac{1}{g(y(x))} \ob{\frac{dy}{dx}\ dx}^{dy} \amp = \int f(x)\ dx</mrow>
				<mrow> \int \frac{1}{g(y)} \ dy \amp = \int f(x)\ dx,</mrow>
			</md>
			which justifies the integration with respect to different variables.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="sov-method-examples-basic">
		<title>Basic Examples</title>

		<p>
			Let's begin with a few warm-up problems to build confidence with the steps of separation of variables. These examples are straightforward: the equations are already in separable form or can be made separable with little algebra. Focus on the main steps of the method: verify that the equation is separable, separate the variables, integrate both sides, and then solve for <m>y</m>.
		</p>

		<exercise label="chkpt-sov-method-identify-separable">
			<title>Is This Equation Separable?</title>
			<statement>
				<p>Which of the following differential equations are separable?</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = x e^y</m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>Yes! This is separable since we can write it as <m>dy/dx = f(x) \cdot g(y)</m>.</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{x}{1 + y^2}</m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>Correct. This can be separated as <m>(1 + y^2)dy = x dx</m>.</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>Nope. This equation is not separable because the right-hand side cannot be factored into a product of functions of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> separately.</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\ds y' = \ln(x+y)</m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>Not separable. The variables are entangled inside the logarithm.</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

		<example xml:id="sov-method-basic-examples">
			<title>Warm-Up: Basic Separable Equations</title>

				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solution to each of the following differential equations using the separation of variables method.
						<me>
							1.\quad \frac{dy}{dx} = x^2, \qquad
							2.\quad \frac{dy}{dx} = y^2, \qquad
							3.\quad \frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{x}{y^2} = 0
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					The first two we'll solve side-by-side using the <xref ref="sov-method" text="custom">separation of variables method</xref>.
				</p>
				<sidebyside widths="45% 10% 45%" valign="top">
					<paragraphs>
						<title> <m>1.\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = x^2</m> </title>
					</paragraphs>
					<p/>
					<paragraphs>
						<title> <m>2.\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2</m> </title>
					</paragraphs>
				</sidebyside>
				<p>
					<xref ref="sov-step-1" text="custom">Step 1</xref> - Verify that the equations are separable.
				</p>
				<sidebyside widths="25% 30% 25%" valign="top" margins="2% 18%">
					<p>
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} =
							\underset{\large f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\ul{x^2}}}} \cdot
							\underset{\large g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{\textcolor{green}{\ul{1}}}}
						</me>
					</p>
					<p/>
					<p>
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} =
							\underset{\large f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\ul{1}}}} \cdot
							\underset{\large g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{\textcolor{green}{\ul{y^2}}}}
						</me>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
				<p>
					<xref ref="sov-step-2" text="custom">Step 2</xref> - Separate variables and integrate:
				</p>
				<sidebyside widths="25% 30% 25%" valign="top" margins="2% 18%">
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> 1\ dy		\amp = x^2\ dx </mrow>
							<mrow> \int 1\ dy	\amp = \int x^2\ dx </mrow>
							<mrow> y + c_1		\amp = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + c_2 </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
					<p/>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> y^{-2}\ dy			\amp = 1\ dx </mrow>
							<mrow> \int y^{-2}\ dy		\amp = \int 1\ dx </mrow>
							<mrow> -\frac{1}{y} + c_1	\amp = x + c_2 </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
				<p>
					<xref ref="sov-step-3" text="custom">Step 3</xref> - Solve for <m>y</m> and combine constants:
				</p>
				<sidebyside widths="44% 10% 44%" valign="top" margins="1% 1%">
					<p>
						<me>
							\boxed{\ \ y = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + c\ \ } \quad (c = c_2 - c_1)
						</me>
					</p>
					<p/>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> \amp\frac{1}{y} = -x + c  \quad (c = c_2 - c_1)</mrow>
							<mrow> \amp\boxed{\ \ y = \frac{1}{-x + c}\ \ } </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
				<paragraphs>
					<title> <m>3.\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{x}{y^2} = 0</m> </title>
					<p>
						<xref ref="sov-step-1" text="custom">Step 1</xref>. First, rewrite the equation
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{x}{y^2}
						</me>.
					</p>

					<p>
						and show it is separable:
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = (-x)\cdot\left(\frac{1}{y^2}\right)
						</me>.
					</p>

					<p>
						<xref ref="sov-step-2" text="custom">Step 2</xref>. Now, separate the variables
						<me> y^2 dy = -x dx, </me>
					</p>

					<p>
						and integrate both sides:
						<md>
							<mrow> \int y^2\ dy \amp = \int -x\ dx </mrow>
							<mrow> \frac{y^3}{3} + c_1 \amp = -\frac{x^2}{2} + c_2 </mrow>.
						</md>
					</p>

					<p>
						<xref ref="sov-step-3" text="custom">Step 3</xref>. Combine constants and isolate <m>y</m>:
						<me>
							\frac{y^3}{3} = -\frac{x^2}{2} + c \quad\Rightarrow\quad \boxed{\ \ y = \left(-\frac{3}{2}x^2 + c_1\right)^{1/3}\ \ }
						</me>
					</p>
				</paragraphs>
			</solution>
		</example>

	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="sov-method-examples-initial">
		<title>Initial-Value Problems</title>

		<p>
			Once you've found the general solution to a separable equation, you can often refine it into a particular solution using an initial condition. These next examples show how to use the same separation steps, then substitute the initial condition to determine the constant.
		</p>

		<example><title> <q><m>\pm</m></q> in the Solution </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Using separation of variables, solve the differential equation
				</p>

				<me>
					\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{\cos x}{y}, 	\quad y(0) = -5
				</me>.
			</statement>

			<solution>

				<p>
					The equation is separable since it can be written as:
					<me>\ds  \frac{dy}{dx} = \big( \cos x \big) \cdot \left( \frac{1}{y} \right).</me>
					Now we apply the separation of variables method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Divide <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow> y\ dy	\amp = \cos(x)\ dx	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top middle">
						
						<p>
							Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m> <m>\vphantom{\ds\int}</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>		\int y\ dy	\amp = \int \cos(x)\ dx	</mrow>
								<mrow>	\frac{y^2}{2}	\amp = \sin(x) + c		</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>

					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top top">
						
						<p>
							<line>	Isolate &amp;					</line>
							<line>	Combine <m>\quad\rightarrow</m>	</line>
							<line>	Constants						</line>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\frac{y^2}{2}	\amp = \sin(x) + c							</mrow>
								<mrow>				y^2	\amp = 2\sin(x) + \os{\large c}{\boxed{2c}}	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>

				</p>

				<p>
					
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">

						<p>
							General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	y(x)	\amp = \pm\sqrt{2\sin(x) + c}	</mrow>
							</md>.
						</p>
						
					</sidebyside>

				</p>

				<p>
					The <m>\pm</m> sign in <m>y</m> means that the general solution includes both the positive and negative versions of this solution. However, since the particular solution must satisfy the initial condition, <m>y(0) = -5</m>, then only one of <q><m>+</m></q> or <q><m>-</m></q> can be used. Substituting the initial condition into the general solution tells us which one to keep. In particular,
					<md>
						<mrow>	-5	\amp = -\sqrt{2\sin(0) + c} = -\sqrt{0 + c} = -\sqrt{c}	</mrow>
						<mrow>	5	\amp = \sqrt{c} \quad \implies \quad c = 25				</mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, the solution to the initial-value problem is:
					<me>
						y(x) = -\sqrt{2\sin(x) + 25}
					</me>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example><title> Some Initial-Valued Problems </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the particular solution to each of the initial-value problems
					<me>
						z' - 1 = z^2, \quad z(4) = 9
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>

				<p>
					This differential equation is first order and separable since
					<md>
						<mrow> z' - 1 \amp = z^2							</mrow>
						<mrow> z' \amp = z^2 + 1							</mrow>
						<mrow> z' \amp = \big( 1 \big) \big( z^2 + 1 \big)  </mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, we can apply the separation of variables method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Divide <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\frac{1}{z^2+1}dz	\amp = 1\ dt	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top middle">
						
						<p>
							Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m> <m>\vphantom{\ds\int}</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\int\frac{1}{z^2+1}\ dz	\amp = \int 1\ dt	</mrow>
								<mrow>				\arctan z	\amp = t + c		</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							<line>	Isolate &amp;					</line>
							<line>	Combine <m>\quad\rightarrow</m>	</line>
							<line>	Constants						</line>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\arctan z	\amp = t + c	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	z	\amp = \tan(t+c)	</mrow>	
							</md>.
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					Substituting, <m>z(4) = 9</m>, into the general solution, we get
					<md>
						<mrow>	9 = \tan(4+c) \implies	\amp\ \tan^{-1}(9) = 4 + c	</mrow>
						<mrow>							\amp\ \tan^{-1}(9) - 4 = c	</mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, the solution to the intial-valued problem is
					<aside><title> ⚠️ Warning </title>
						<p>
							If you approximate <m>c</m> (e.g. <m>-2.54</m>), the solution
							<me>
								z = \tan(t - 2.54)
							</me>,
							no longer satisfies the initial condition <m>z(4) = 9</m>.
						</p>
					</aside>
					<me>
						z = \tan(t + \tan^{-1}(9) - 4)
					</me>
					
				</p>
				
			</solution>
		</example>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="sov-method-examples-algebraic">
		<title>Algebraic Rearrangement Required</title>

		<p>
			Not all equations start in a clean separable form. Sometimes you'll need to manipulate the equation—like isolating <m>dy/dx</m>—before you can separate the variables. The next example illustrates this kind of preparation step.
		</p>

		<example>
			<title>Algebra Required: Making the Equation Separable</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution to the differential equation:
				</p>
				<me> y^2 y' - 1 = 6x^2 </me>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					This equation is not obviously separable as written, so we begin by solving for <m>y'</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> y^2 y' \amp = 6x^2 + 1 </mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dx} \amp = \frac{6x^2 + 1}{y^2} = \big( 6x^2 + 1 \big)\cdot \left( \frac{1}{y^2} \right) </mrow>
					</md>
					This is now in separable form.
				</p>
				<p>
					We now separate and integrate:
					<md>
						<mrow> y^2 dy \amp = (6x^2 + 1) dx </mrow>
						<mrow> \int y^2 dy \amp = \int (6x^2 + 1) dx </mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{y^3}{3} \amp = 2x^3 + x + c </mrow>
					</md>
					Multiplying through and isolating <m>y</m> gives the general solution:
					<me> y = \sqrt[3]{6x^3 + 3x + c} </me>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="sov-method-examples-implicit">
		<title>Implicit Solutions</title>
		<p>
			In some cases, even after integrating both sides, it's not possible to isolate <m>y</m> explicitly. These solutions are called <em>implicit</em>, and they still provide complete information about the relationship between variables. Let's look at an example where this happens.
		</p>

		<example><title> An Implicit Solution </title>
			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Solve the initial-value problem
						<me>
							Q Q' + e^Q Q' = t, \quad Q(2) = 0
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				<solution>

					<p>
						Since all the <m>Q</m> terms are on the left and all the <m>t</m> terms are on the right, we can just factor out <m>Q'</m> on the left to separate the equation.
					</p>

					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
							
							<p>
								Divide <m>\rightarrow</m>
							</p>

							<p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	\left(Q + e^Q\right)dQ	\amp = tdt	</mrow>
								</md>
							</p>

						</sidebyside>
					</p>

					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top middle">
							
							<p>
								Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m> <m>\vphantom{\ds\int}</m>
							</p>

							<p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	\int \left(Q + e^Q\right)dQ	\amp = \int t\ dt			</mrow>
									<mrow>			\frac12 Q^2 + e^Q	\amp = \frac{1}{2}t^2 + c	</mrow>
								</md>
							</p>

						</sidebyside>
					</p>

					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top middle">
							
							<p>
								<line>	Isolate &amp;					</line>
								<line>	Combine <m>\quad\rightarrow</m>	</line>
								<line>	Constants						</line>
							</p>

							<p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	Q^2 + 2e^Q	\amp = t^2 + \us{c}{\boxed{2c}}	</mrow>.
								</md>
							</p>

						</sidebyside>
					</p>

					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
							
							<p>
								General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
							</p>

							<p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	\left(Q(t)\right)^2 + 2e^{Q(t)} = t^2 + c	</mrow>.
								</md>.
							</p>

						</sidebyside>
					</p>

					<p>
						Note that although <m>Q</m> is a function of <m>t</m>, there is no nice way to isolate a single <m>Q</m> on one side and a function of purely <m>t</m> on the other. In these cases, we say <m>Q</m> depends implicity on <m>t</m> and we leave the general solution in this implicit form.
					</p>

					<p>
						Despite being an implicit solution, we can still find <m>c</m> using <m>Q(2) = 0</m> by setting <m>t=2</m> in the general solution to get
						<md>
							<mrow>	\left(Q(2)\right)^2 + 2e^{Q(2)}	\amp = 2^2 + c								</mrow>
							<mrow>		\left(0\right)^2 + 2e^{0}	\amp = 4 + c								</mrow>
							<mrow>								2	\amp = 4 + c	\quad\implies\quad c = -2	</mrow>
						</md>.
						Therefore, the particular implicit solution to this problem is given by
						<me>
							\left(Q(t)\right)^2 + 2e^{Q(t)} = t^2 - 2
						</me>.
					</p>

				</solution>
			</p>		
		</example>

		<exercise label="chkpt-sov-explicit-vs-implicit">
			<title>Explicit or Implicit?</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which of the following equations represent an <strong>implicit</strong> solution to a differential equation?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>y = \tan(x) + c</m></statement>
					<feedback><p>No—this is an explicit solution since <m>y</m> is written as a function of <m>x</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>y^2 + \ln y = x + c</m></statement>
					<feedback><p>Correct. You can't isolate <m>y</m> without solving a nonlinear equation, so this is an implicit solution.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>(Q(t))^2 + 2e^{Q(t)} = t^2 - 2</m></statement>
					<feedback><p>Yes—this matches the example you just saw and defines <m>Q</m> only implicitly.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>z = \tan(t + c)</m></statement>
					<feedback><p>No—this is an explicit expression for <m>z</m> as a function of <m>t</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="sov-method-examples-special-cases">
		<title>Special Cases and Pitfalls</title>

		<p>
			The last examples in this section highlight two special cases: equations involving absolute values and constants, and how to correctly combine constants after integrating. These examples also reinforce algebraic precision—particularly when logarithmic or square root expressions are involved.
		</p>

		<example><title> Dealing with Absolute Values </title>
			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solution to the differential equation
						<me>
							x\frac{dy}{dx} + 10x^2y = 6x^2
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</p>

			<p>
				<solution>

					<p>
						This differential equation is first order and separable since
						<md>
							<mrow>	x\frac{dy}{dx} + 10x^2y	\amp = 6x^2										</mrow>
							<mrow>			\frac{dy}{dx}	\amp = \frac{6x^2}{x}\left(6x^2 - 10x^2y\right)	</mrow>
							<mrow>			\frac{dy}{dx}	\amp = 6x - 10xy = (2x)(3 - 5y)					</mrow>
						</md>
						Therefore, we can apply the separation of variables method.
					</p>

					<p>
						<em>Note, the boxed expressions below are where we combined constants.</em>
					</p>

					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="30% 70%" valigns="middle middle">
							
							<p>
								Divide <m>\rightarrow</m>
							</p>

							<p>
								<m> \ds \qquad\frac{1}{3 - 5y}dy = 2x\ dx </m>
							</p>

						</sidebyside>
					</p>

					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="30% 70%" valigns="top middle">
							
							<p>
								Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m>
							</p>

							<p>
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\int \frac{1}{3 - 5y}dy	\amp = \int 2x\ dx \quad
										\left(
										\begin{array}{c}
											u = 3-5y,\\
											du = -5dx
										\end{array}
										\right)
									</mrow>
									<mrow>	-\frac{1}{5}\ln|3 - 5y|	\amp = x^2 + c	</mrow>			
								</md>
							</p>

						</sidebyside>
					</p>

					<p>

						<sidebyside widths="30% 70%" valigns="top top">
							
							<p>
								<line>	Isolate &amp;	<m>\quad\rightarrow</m>	</line>
								<line>	Combine									</line>
								<line>	Constants								</line>
							</p>

							<p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	\ln|3 - 5y|	\amp = -5x^2 - 5c								</mrow>
									<mrow>	|3 - 5y|	\amp = e^{-5x^2 - 5c}							</mrow>
									<mrow>		3 - 5y	\amp = \pm e^{-5x^2 - 5c}						</mrow>
									<mrow>		3 - 5y	\amp = \boxed{\pm e^{-5c}}\ e^{-5x^2}			</mrow>
									<mrow>			5y	\amp = c e^{-5x^2} + 3							</mrow>
									<mrow>			y	\amp = \boxed{\frac{c}{5}}\ e^{-5x^2} + \frac35	</mrow>
								</md>
							</p>

						</sidebyside>

					</p>

					<p>

						<sidebyside widths="30% 70%" valigns="middle middle">
							
							<p>
								General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
							</p>

							<p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	y = ce^{-5x^2} + \frac35	</mrow>.
								</md>.
							</p>

						</sidebyside>

					</p>

					<p>
						The absolute value in the solution came from the <m>y</m> integral, which was later replaced by <m>\pm</m>. The <m>\pm</m> was combined into <m>c</m> since changing the sign of a constant doesn't change the fact that it is a constant.
					</p>

				</solution>
			</p>
		</example>
	</paragraphs>

	<p>
		The separation of variables method is a flexible and powerful tool for solving a wide range of differential equations, including nonlinear ones. As you've seen, the method is systematic: separate, integrate, and isolate. While the mechanics of the method are straightforward, the complexity often lies in the algebraic manipulation and integration.
	</p>

	<fact label="sov-method-cyu">
		<statement>
			<p>
				Answer the following questions:
				<task label="chkpt-sov-method-1">
					<title> SOV and Nonlinear Equations </title>
					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							The separation of variables method cannot be applied to non-linear differential equations.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Being able to solve non-linear differential equations is one of the strengths of the separation of variables method.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>
				<task label="chkpt-sov-method-2" randomize="true">
					<title> Sort the Steps in Order </title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							CONVERT TO PARSONS.. Suppose you want to use separation of variables method to determine the general solution of the differential equation
							<men xml:id="chkpt-sov-method-examples-1-eqn">
								\ds \frac{dq}{dt} - 3qt^2 = 2q
							</men>.
						</p>
						<p>
							Match the scrambled tasks (on the left) to the task order (on the right) that it should be performed to use this method.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<feedback>
						<p>
							Review the <xref ref="sov-method" text="custom">SOV Method</xref>.
						</p>
					</feedback>

					<cardsort>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<line><m>\text{Equation is 1st-order ✅}</m></line>
								</p>
							</premise>
							
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 1}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>

						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<m>\ds \frac{dq}{dt} = q(2 + 3t^2)</m>
								</p>
							</premise>
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 2}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<m>\ds \frac{1}{q}\ dq = (2 + 3t^2)\ dt</m>
								</p>
							</premise>
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 3}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<m>\ds \int \frac{1}{q} dq = \int (2 + 3t^2) dt</m>
								</p>
							</premise>
							
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 4}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<line><m>\ds \ln|q| = 2t^2 + t^3 + c</m></line>
								</p>
							</premise>
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 5}</m>
								</p>	
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<line><m>\ds q = c e\vphantom{|}^{\large 2t^2 + t^3}</m></line>
								</p>
							</premise>
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 6}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
					</cardsort>

				</task>
				<task label="chkpt-sov-method-3">
					<title> Combining Constants </title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Which of the following are valid ways to combine constants when finalizing your solution? Select ALL that apply.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<choices>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										|y|	\amp = e^{2x + c_1}\\ 
										y	\amp = c_2 e^{2x} 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2=\pm e^{c_1}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	|y|	\amp =,	e^{2x + c_1}										</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm e^{2x + c_1}									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm e^{2x} \cdot e^{c_1}							</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	c_2 e^{2x}	\quad \text{where } c_2 = \pm e^{c_1}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										\frac{y^2}{2} \amp = \sin(x) + c_1\\ 
										y^2 \amp = 2\sin(x) + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2 = 2c_1</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	\frac{y^2}{2}	\amp =,	\sin(x) + c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y^2				\amp =,	\sin(x) + 2c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y^2				\amp =,	2\sin(x) + c_2	\quad \text{where } c_2 = 2c_1	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										y^2	\amp = 2\sin(x) + c_2\\ 
										y	\amp = \pm\sqrt{2\sin(x)} + c_3 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_3=\pm \sqrt{c_2}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\quad\sqrt{A + B} \neq \sqrt{A} + \sqrt{B}</m>.
								</p>

								<p>
									Your solution should be written as
									<md>
										<mrow>	y^2	\amp =,	2\sin(x) + c_2											</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm\sqrt{2\sin(x) + c_2}\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										e^y	\amp =	3y + c_1\\ 
										y	\amp =	\ln(3y) + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2= \ln(c_1)</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\ln(A + B) \neq \ln(A) + \ln(B)</m>.
								</p>

								<p>
									Your solution should be
									<md>
										<mrow>	e^y	\amp =,	3y + c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\ln(3y + c_1)\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										xy	\amp =	e^x + c_1\\ 
										y	\amp =	\frac{e^x}{x} + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>\ds c_2=\frac{c_1}{x}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\frac{c_1}{x}</m> is not constant. Instead your solution should be left as
									<md>
										<mrow>	xy	\amp =,	e^x + c_1													</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\frac{e^x + c_1}{x}											</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\frac{e^x}{x} + \frac{c_1}{x}\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										\sqrt{y}	\amp =	c_1e^{3x}\\ 
										y			\amp =	c_2\, e^{6x} 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2= c_1^2</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	\sqrt{y}	\amp =,	c_1e^{3x}									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	(c_1e^{3x})^2								</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	c_1^2(e^{3x})^2								</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	c_2\, e^{6x}\quad \text{where } c_2 = c_1^2	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
					</choices>

				</task>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</fact>

</section>